text: The problem with the conjuring universe is the only person that seems to be able to make a good/great movie within it is James wan no matter how good the premise is. Insidious has been run into the ground and to make things even more wtf, it was ruined by the guy that writes all of them once wan let him take over directing duties. I know wan is extremely busy and sought after but all of this stuff is part of his legacy so I wish he would take a more hands on approach as a producer. He knows what works and even though he was using other people's scripts for the films he did he reworked them to be more effective. His ambitions more than likely expand way past horror but with his guiding hand I think he can do for horror what Kevin feige was able to do for the superhero genre and it would be one hell of a thing to do considering the potential profit margin for these kinds of movies. Several  hundred million dollars at the box office for films that usually max out at around 30-40 million dollars for their budget(with most of them not exceeding 15-20 million) is a lot more impressive than spending 350 mil (plus marketing costs that can get up to almost the same amount) to pull in a billion(+).

text: Let’s examine how Annabelle managed to escape. Strap in. This might be a while.  1. Aside from the whole premature celebration, why did Lorraine warren, who can sense spirits, believe Annabelle was contained? In her own home?  2. Annabelle has multiple moments where she could have easily done what she would proceed to do in the movie. So why would she wait until behind SACRED glass to awaken them?  3. If you recall Annabelle: Creation, the doll was easily contained by being surrounded by pages of the Bible. So how did she manage to escape a case of sacred glass that was blessed by a priest?  Finally, Annabelle had been sated for who knows how long, and not once had she been awakened. And if she’s awoken by touch, how did the person placing her in the case not wake her up?   All in all, the idea that she wakes up and goes through this is entirely preposterous. Not only that, but the entire plot is set by that one moment, making it a heaping pile of bullshit.
author: Joshua Schneider
